# WHY THIS IS .mdtodo INSTEAD OF .md

The snapshot tool runs the interpreter backend first (the `dev`/`llvm` backends
only run as comparison passes, with crash protection). The interpreter currently
panics on Dict.join_map, so this snapshot can't pass â€” saving it as `.mdtodo`
keeps the test cases on record without breaking `zig build snapshot`/`zig build
test`. Rename to `.md` once the interpreter bug below is fixed.

# THE BUG

Calling `Dict.join_map` in the interpreter panics with `reached unreachable`
at `src/interpreter_layout/store.zig:2498` inside `fromTypeVar` for a rigid
type variable that has a `where`-clause constraint but no active runtime
substitution. The dev backend (default for `roc repl`) doesn't hit this â€” its
codegen uses `src/layout/store.zig`, which falls back to ZST for the same
situation. A separate dev-backend bug (ZST struct destructuring in for-loops,
`LirCodeGen.zig`) was fixed in this branch and is what makes the dev path work
end-to-end.

# ROOT CAUSE

1. `join_map : Dict(a, b), (a, b -> Dict(x, y)) -> Dict(x, y) where [x.is_eq : x, x -> Bool]`
2. `Interpreter.instantiateType` rewrites the signature's rigids to fresh flex
   vars (`a', b', x', y'`) via `Instantiator{ .rigid_behavior = .fresh_flex }`.
3. The lambda arg's CT type was type-checked using the function signature's
   expected return type, so unifying it with the instantiated param brings the
   ORIGINAL rigid `x` into contact with the fresh flex `x'`. Unification then
   hits `unifyFlex` -> `.rigid` case at `src/check/unify.zig:430`, which
   merges the flex INTO the rigid (preserving parametricity). After this,
   `resolveVar(x') = rigid x` with its `is_eq` constraint intact.
4. `prepareCallWithFuncVar` then calls `getRuntimeLayout(substituted_ret)` for
   `Dict(x, y)`. Inside `fromTypeVar`, the nominal type's backing tag-union
   eventually reaches the rigid `x` while a `.tuple` is the immediate pending
   container (and `.list` is one level up). The current logic only defaults to
   ZST/Dec when the immediate container is `.list` or `.box`, so it falls
   through to the `unreachable` at line 2498.
5. Crucially, the call's `rigid_subst` entries (which WOULD let layout
   computation deeply substitute `x -> Str`) are populated AFTER
   `prepareCallWithFuncVar` returns â€” that ordering exists so cycle-detection
   can prune entries that unification redirected back to their source rigid.
   So at the moment of the panic, the substitution is genuinely not yet
   visible to the layout layer.

# WHAT I TRIED (none of these are right)

- **ZST fallback in `interpreter_layout/store.zig`** (mirroring
  `src/layout/store.zig`'s handling): turns the panic into a downstream
  "Invalid free". The wrong (ZST / `list_of_zst`) layout gets cached and
  miscompared against the real `Dict(Str, F64)` value's allocation during
  decref. The dev backend gets away with the same fallback because it
  monomorphizes during MIR codegen rather than relying on runtime layout
  lookups.

- **Extend `getRuntimeLayout`'s constrained-rigid guard to look through
  nominal_type / tuple / record / tag_union args, returning `TypeMismatch`**:
  causes `prepareCallWithFuncVar` to skip (good) but the same error then
  propagates from one of the ~58 other `getRuntimeLayout` call sites
  (notably during result inspection), turning every Dict.join_map call into
  "Evaluation error: error.TypeMismatch".

- **Skip the `prepareCallWithFuncVar` layout call + the numeric-literal
  repoint in `evalLookupLocal` when the type has an unresolvable rigid**:
  bypasses two known call sites but the wrong layout still leaks in
  elsewhere â€” including inside the body of `join_map` where `Dict.empty()`
  is initialized with `Dict(_, _)` rigids and never properly upgraded as
  real `(Str, F64)` entries flow in.

# WHAT A REAL FIX PROBABLY LOOKS LIKE

The root cause is that `rigid_subst` isn't visible to layout computation
deeply (it's consulted only at the top level of `getRuntimeLayout`'s
substitution loop). Two plausible directions:

- **Publish `rigid_subst` mid-`prepareCallWithFuncVar`** (after unification,
  before the layout call), with the existing cycle-detection logic moved
  earlier. This makes the layout layer's existing rigid-resolution
  machinery actually find the substitution.

- **Teach `fromTypeVar` to consult a `rigid_subst`-backed `TypeScope`
  deeply.** Today the layout store only follows `type_scope` when
  `caller_module_idx` is non-null (cross-module case). Passing a non-empty
  scope built from `rigid_subst` for same-module calls would make the
  nested-rigid case resolve naturally.

Either approach also needs to handle the `Dict.empty()`-inside-`join_map`-body
upgrade case so the runtime list correctly transitions from `list_of_zst` to
`list` of `(Str, F64)` as elements flow in.
